<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-10-02T21:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-10-02T21:00:00-05:00" n="425" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/4114: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Welles</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-10-02T21:00:00-05:00">October 2, 1933—9
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 10:58 p.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>333. Batista has just sent me word that he has placed a guard around
                                the National Hotel to prevent any further looting by soldiers and
                                especially distribution of contents of wine cellars. He assures me
                                that the lives of all the officers now in custody will be personally
                                guaranteed by himself and that I may feel confident that order will
                                be maintained in the city tonight.</p>
                            <p>From all information I can obtain, in view of the difficulty of
                                communications, all sections of the city have been relatively quiet
                                during the past 2 hours.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>